Overview of the performance Greedy-Marginals-MST.

Table 3 gives an overview of the experimental results for Greedy-PreFair (Algorithm 2) compared to MST across all datasets with a singular privacy budget of ϵ=1italic-ϵ1\epsilon=1. Across all datasets, the cost of fairness is relatively low and does not significantly hinder accuracy.

We have also measured the overall runtime for Greedy-PreFair compared to MST. Greedy-PreFair performs slightly better than MST in most cases and the improvement increases with the increase in the size of the dataset (Table 3). This is a result of the greedy optimization where Greedy-PreFair considers fewer options than MST for neighbors of outcome attributes. We measured the runtime of Exponential-PreFair as well. Even on small datasets it takes 10 times longer than either MST or Greedy-PreFair and is prohibitively expensive to run on a large dataset222Exponential-PreFair has a significantly higher runtime overhead. As Exponential-PreFair runs in exponential time we were only able to measure performance on the Adult and Compas datasets.
In the low privacy regime (ϵ=0.1italic-ϵ0.1\epsilon=0.1), Exponential-PreFair can take up to 10 times longer than MST, taking on average 1344 seconds to run.
In larger datasets, this overhead becomes prohibitively expensive as it scales exponentially in the number of attributes..
